##Paried T-Test for Sleep Length

sleep_length <- data.frame(group = rep(c("apple", "whoop"), each = 44),
                length = c(apple$`Sleep Length`,  whoop$`Sleep Length`))

#Summary Stat 
sleep_length %>%
  group_by(group) %>%
  summarise(count = n(),
            mean = mean(length),
            sd = sd(length))
## # A tibble: 2  4
##   group count  mean    sd
##   <chr> <int> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 apple    44  480   67.6
## 2 whoop    44  477.  68.7
#Boxplot for summary stat
ggplot(data = sleep_length, aes(x = group, y = length)) + geom_boxplot() + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent") 

#Plot Paired Data
apple_sl <- subset(sleep_length,  group == "apple", length,
                 drop = TRUE)

whoop_sl <- subset(sleep_length,  group == "whoop", length,
                 drop = TRUE)

pd <- paired(apple_sl, whoop_sl)
plot(pd, type = "profile") + theme_bw()

#Normality Test
difference <- with(sleep_length, 
        length[group == "apple"] - length[group == "whoop"])

shapiro.test(difference) 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  difference
## W = 0.77932, p-value = 1.067e-06
hist(difference)

wilcox.test(apple_sl, whoop_sl, paired = TRUE)
## Warning in wilcox.test.default(apple_sl, whoop_sl, paired = TRUE): cannot
## compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  apple_sl and whoop_sl
## V = 669.5, p-value = 0.04225
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

##Paired T-Test for Calories Burned Workout

apple_cal_burn_df <- apple %>%
  separate_rows(`Calories Burned Workout`, sep = ",") %>%
  mutate(`Calories Burned Workout` = str_trim(`Calories Burned Workout`, "both"))

whoop_cal_burn_df <- whoop %>%
  separate_rows(`Calories Burned Workout`, sep = ",") %>%
  mutate(`Calories Burned Workout` = str_trim(`Calories Burned Workout`, "both"))

apple_cal_burn_df$`Calories Burned Workout` <- as.numeric(apple_cal_burn_df$`Calories Burned Workout`)
whoop_cal_burn_df$`Calories Burned Workout` <- as.numeric(whoop_cal_burn_df$`Calories Burned Workout`)

workout_cal <- data.frame(group = rep(c("apple", "whoop"), each = 61),
                cal = c(apple_cal_burn_df$`Calories Burned Workout`,  whoop_cal_burn_df$`Calories Burned Workout`))

#Summary Stat 
workout_cal %>%
  group_by(group) %>%
  summarise(count = n(),
            mean = mean(cal, na.rm = TRUE),
            sd = sd(cal, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 2  4
##   group count  mean    sd
##   <chr> <int> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 apple    61  363.  228.
## 2 whoop    61  271.  274.
#Boxplot for summary stat
ggplot(data = workout_cal, aes(x = group, y = cal)) + geom_boxplot() + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent")
